### Footnotes

<span id="fn_913"></span>[164:1](kj052.htm#fr_917.md) This name signifies
"bear-moor." The name is now generally pronounced *Kumano*.

<span id="fn_914"></span>[164:2](kj052.htm#fr_918.md) Motowori ingeniously
conjectures the text of this passage <span id="img_16500"></span>
![](img/16500.jpg), which makes no sense, to be a copyist's error for
<span id="img_16501"></span> ![](img/16501.jpg), which <span
id="page_166">p. 166</span> gives the meaning rendered in the
translation. The running hand form of <span id="img_16602"></span>
![](img/16602.jpg) might well be mistaken for that of the single
character <span id="img_16603"></span> ![](img/16603.jpg). The editor of
1687 is less happy in his conjecture that the character intended may be
<span id="img_16604"></span> ![](img/16604.jpg), "crocodile." This
incident of the bear was thought important by the compiler for a mention
of it to be inserted in his Preface. (See [p. 5](kj007.htm#page_5).md).

<span id="fn_915"></span>[164:3](kj052.htm#fr_919.md) The signification of
this name is not clear. Taking *zhi* as an apocopated *nigori’ed* form
of the Postposition *shita*, we might suppose *taka-kura-zhi* to signify
"under the high store house" in allusion to the legend which forms the
subject of this section. There are, however, reasons for doubting this
etymology. (See Motowori's Commentary, Vol. XVIII, p. 48). In the
Preface we have simply *Takahura*, without the final syllable *zhi*; but
the omission of *zhi* in that place is almost certainly to be accounted
for on euphonic grounds.

<span id="fn_916"></span>[164:4](kj052.htm#fr_920.md) This note to the
original is believed to be an interpolation,

<span id="fn_917"></span>[164:5](kj052.htm#fr_921.md) <span
id="img_16603"></span> ![](img/16603.jpg). Motowori avers that the
character <span id="img_16604"></span> ![](img/16604.jpg), "cross," has
no importance, and should be neglected in reading. But this assertion
seems gratuitous in the face of, for instance, such a Chinese locution
as <span id="img_16605"></span> ![](img/16605.jpg). We may be justified,
perhaps, in paying no special heed to the Numeral "one" in this place,
which Motowori neglects in his *kana* reading of the text.

<span id="fn_918"></span>[164:6](kj052.htm#fr_922.md) *I.e.*, they fell
down cut to pieces before they had even been cut at with this wonderful
sword.

<span id="fn_919"></span>[165:7](kj052.htm#fr_923.md) The character <span
id="img_16606"></span> ![](img/16606.jpg), "august," which should form
the penultimate member of this compound name, is here omitted.

<span id="fn_920"></span>[165:8](kj052.htm#fr_924.md) See Sect. I, Note 5.

<span id="fn_921"></span>[165:9](kj052.htm#fr_925.md) See Sect. VIII, Note
7.

<span id="fn_922"></span>[165:10](kj052.htm#fr_926.md) See Sect. IX, Note
18.

<span id="fn_923"></span>[165:11](kj052.htm#fr_927.md) Conf. Sect. X, Note
1.

<span id="fn_924"></span>[165:12](kj052.htm#fr_928.md) The humble character
<span id="img_16607"></span> ![](img/16607.jpg), "servant," is here
used.

<span id="fn_925"></span>[165:13](kj052.htm#fr_929.md) *Sazhi-futsu no
kami*. The translator follows Tanigaha Shisei in considering *sazhi*
(Tanigaha Shisei in his "Perpetual Commentary" reads *sashi* without the
*nigori*) to mean "thrust." For the rendering of *futsu* as "snap" in
this and the two following names *conf*. Sect. VIII, Note 8. Moribe,
however, in his "*Ikzu no Chi-waki*," asserts that *futsu* is but an
alternative form of *futo*, "broad," "thick," or "vast," as shown by the
existence of the phrase *ma-futsu no kagami*, "a true vast mirror."

<span id="fn_926"></span>[165:14](kj052.htm#fr_930.md) *Mika-futsu no
kami*.

<span id="fn_927"></span>[165:15](kj052.htm#fr_931.md) *Futsu no mi tame*.

<span id="fn_928"></span>[165:16](kj052.htm#fr_932.md) <span
id="page_167">p. 167</span> The name of this place, which is in the
province of Yamato, seems to signify "above the rock." It is well known
as the Pillow-Word for the syllables *furu*.

<span id="fn_929"></span>[165:17](kj052.htm#fr_933.md) Properly what is
known to Anglo-Orientals as a "godown."

<span id="fn_930"></span>[165:18](kj052.htm#fr_934.md) The sentence here
placed between braces is proposed by Motowori to supplement an evident
